    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Cramps during your period</span></h1>\n    <p>If you&apos;re having mild cramps, don&apos;t worry, it&apos;s totally normal since you are on your period right now. Typically the cramps can start 1 to 3 days before your period, and peaks 24 hours after the onset of your period and subsides in 2 to 3 days.</p>\n    <p>Ff the cramps feel really strong and make you uncomfortable, there are a few things you can do to feel better. One thing is to use a warm heating pad on your stomach or take a warm bath. This can help relax your muscles and make the pain go away. You could also try doing some gentle exercises, like walking or stretching, which can help with the pain too.</p>\n    <p>Another thing that might help is taking over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen or Aleve Feminax. Make sure to read the product prescription well, or ask your guardian for help.</p>\n    <p>In some cases cramps can become too extreme and get in the way of your daily activities, in this case it&rsquo;s good practice to contact your doctor. They can help you figure out what&apos;s going on and suggest the best options to make you feel better. Sometimes they might recommend stronger medicine or other treatments that can help you manage the pain.</p>\n    <p>Especially if you have just started menstruating, the amount of cramps can differ per period and can either increase or decrease in the next couple of cycles. Let&rsquo;s see how next month will go, and if they are getting better or worse.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Cramps during your follicular phase</span></h1>\n    <p> Cramps during the follicular phase of the menstrual cycle are generally less common compared to cramps during ovulation or the luteal phase. </p>\n    <p> During the follicular phase, the follicles in the ovaries begin to develop and mature, getting ready to release an egg. Some women may experience mild cramping or discomfort during this phase, but it is not as prevalent or intense as the cramps that can occur during ovulation or the menstrual period.</p>\n    <p>If you do experience cramps during the follicular phase, it\'s important to pay attention to the nature and severity of the pain. If the cramps are mild and brief, they are generally considered normal and nothing to worry about. However, if the cramps are severe, persistent, or significantly interfere with your daily activities, it\'s a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional for further evaluation.</p>\n    <p>Remember, every person\'s body is unique, and experiences during the menstrual cycle can vary. If you have specific concerns or questions about cramping during the follicular phase or any other aspect of your menstrual cycle, it\'s best to seek guidance from a trusted adult or healthcare provider for personalized advice.</p>\n \n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html> \n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Cramps during your ovulation</span></h1>\n    <p>Cramps during ovulation are relatively common and considered normal for many women. The medical term for these cramps is \"mittelschmerz,\" which comes from German and means \"middle pain.\" Mittelschmerz occurs around the time of ovulation when the ovary releases an egg.</p>\n    <p>During ovulation, the egg bursts out of the ovary, and this can cause some discomfort or mild cramping in the lower abdomen. The cramps are typically on one side of the abdomen, depending on which ovary is releasing the egg. Some girls and women may feel a twinge or sharp pain, while others may experience a dull ache or mild cramping sensation.</p>\n    <p>It\'s important to note that not everyone experiences ovulation cramps, and the intensity can vary from person to person. Some individuals may have noticeable cramps, while others may have very mild or no discomfort at all.</p>\n    <p>While ovulation cramps are generally harmless, it\'s essential to pay attention to any severe or persistent pain that significantly interferes with your daily activities. If you have concerns or if the pain is severe, it\'s always a good idea to consult a healthcare professional for further evaluation and guidance.</p>\n    <p>While ovulation cramps are generally harmless, it\'s essential to pay attention to any severe or persistent pain that significantly interferes with your daily activities. If you have concerns or if the pain is severe, it\'s always a good idea to consult a healthcare professional for further evaluation and guidance.</p>\n<p>Remember, everyone\'s body is unique, and the experiences during ovulation can vary. If you have any specific questions or concerns about your personal health, it\'s best to reach out to a trusted adult or healthcare provider for personalized advice.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Cramps during your luteal phase</span></h1>\n    <p>It\'s totally normal to have cramps during your luteal phase. The reason you might experience cramps during this phase is because of something called prostaglandins. These are chemicals that your body releases to help your uterus get ready in case there\'s a fertilized egg. But sometimes, these prostaglandins can cause the muscles in your uterus to squeeze too hard, which leads to cramps.</p>\n    <p>It\'s important to know that not every girl experiences cramps during the luteal phase, and if you do, the intensity can vary. Some girls have mild cramps that feel like a dull ache, while others might have stronger cramps that feel more uncomfortable.</p>\n    <p>But don\'t worry, there are things you can do to help relieve the cramps! Applying a warm heating pad or taking a warm bath can help relax the muscles and make you feel better. You can also try gentle exercises like stretching or going for a walk, as these can help reduce the cramps too.</p>\n    <p>If the cramps become too intense or start to interfere with your daily activities, it\'s a good idea to talk to a trusted adult, like your mom or a healthcare professional. They can give you more guidance and make sure everything is okay.</p>\n    <p>Remember, having cramps during the luteal phase is a normal part of your menstrual cycle. It might not feel great, but it\'s a sign that your body is working the way it should. Just take care of yourself, try some of the tips I mentioned, and reach out for help if you need it. You\'re doing great!</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Cramps during your PMS</span></h1>\n    <p>Experiencing cramps during premenstrual syndrome (PMS) is quite common. PMS refers to a combination of physical, emotional, and behavioral symptoms that occur in the days or weeks leading up to menstruation. Cramping or abdominal discomfort is among the physical symptoms associated with PMS.</p>\n    <p>During PMS, hormonal changes can cause the uterus to contract, leading to cramps. These cramps are often similar to menstrual cramps but occur before the actual period begins. The severity of PMS cramps can vary from person to person, ranging from mild to more intense.</p>\n    <p>While experiencing cramps during PMS is common, it\'s essential to pay attention to the severity of the pain and how it impacts your daily life. If the cramps are severe and significantly interfere with your ability to function, it\'s a good idea to speak with a healthcare professional to rule out any underlying conditions or discuss potential management strategies.</p>\n    <p>Remember, if you have concerns about your PMS symptoms or if they become increasingly severe, it\'s always a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional who can provide personalized advice and guidance.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Fainting during menstruation</span></h1>\n    <p>Fainting during your period can happen, but it is not considered a normal or typical symptom. While some individuals may experience dizziness or light-headedness during menstruation, actually fainting is less common and could be a cause for concern.</p>\n    <p>Fainting, or syncope, can occur due to various reasons, such as a drop in blood pressure, low blood sugar, or dehydration. These factors can sometimes be associated with menstruation but are not directly caused by it.</p>\n    <p>If you frequently experience fainting episodes during your period, it\'s essential to discuss this with a healthcare professional. They can evaluate your overall health, identify any underlying conditions, and provide appropriate guidance and treatment if necessary.</p>\n    <p>In the meantime, it\'s important to take care of yourself during your period by staying hydrated, eating regular and balanced meals, and avoiding prolonged standing or sudden changes in position. If you feel lightheaded or dizzy, it can help to lie down or sit with your head between your knees until the sensation passes.</p>\n    <p>Remember, everyone\'s body is unique, and individual experiences during menstruation can vary. If you have concerns about fainting or any other symptoms you experience during your period, it\'s best to seek guidance from a healthcare professional for a proper evaluation.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Fainting</span></h1>\n    <p>Fainting during any phase of the menstrual cycle is generally not considered a normal occurrence. While some individuals may experience dizziness or light-headedness during certain phases of their menstrual cycle due to hormonal changes, fainting itself is relatively uncommon and should be evaluated by a healthcare professional.</p>\n    <p>Fainting, also known as syncope, can be caused by various factors, including a drop in blood pressure, low blood sugar, dehydration, or certain medical conditions. These factors can occur at any time during the menstrual cycle, but fainting specifically related to the menstrual cycle is not typical.</p>\n    <p>If you are experiencing fainting episodes at any point during your menstrual cycle, it is important to consult with a healthcare professional. They can assess your overall health, identify any underlying conditions, and provide appropriate guidance and treatment.</p>\n    <p>In the meantime, prioritize your well-being by staying hydrated, eating regular and balanced meals, and practicing good self-care. If you feel lightheaded or dizzy, it can be helpful to rest, lie down, or sit with your head between your knees until the sensation passes.</p>\n    <p> Remember, if you are experiencing fainting episodes or any concerning symptoms, it\'s best to seek medical advice from a healthcare professional for a thorough evaluation and personalized guidance .</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Mood swings during menstruation</span></h1>\n    <p>Experiencing mood swings during your period is quite common and considered a normal part of the menstrual cycle. Many girls and women may notice changes in their mood and emotions leading up to and during their period.</p>\n    <p>The hormonal fluctuations that occur during the menstrual cycle can influence neurotransmitters in the brain, which can impact mood and emotions. Specifically, the drop in estrogen and progesterone levels before menstruation can contribute to mood changes such as irritability, sadness, anxiety, or feeling more sensitive.</p>\n    <p>These mood swings are often referred to as premenstrual syndrome (PMS) and can vary in severity and duration from person to person. Some individuals may experience mild mood swings, while others may have more pronounced emotional shifts.</p>\n    <p>It\'s important to remember that while mood swings during your period are common, they shouldn\'t interfere significantly with your daily life or overall well-being. If you find that your mood swings are severe, persistent, or greatly affect your ability to function, it may be helpful to seek guidance from a healthcare professional who can provide further support and management strategies.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Mood swings during your follicular phase</span></h1>\n    <p>Mood swings during the follicular phase of the menstrual cycle, which occurs at the beginning of the cycle leading up to ovulation, are generally less common compared to the premenstrual phase. However, it\'s important to note that individuals may still experience some fluctuations in mood during this time due to hormonal changes.</p>\n    <p>During the follicular phase, estrogen levels gradually increase, which can have an impact on mood and emotions. While some individuals may not notice significant mood swings during this phase, others may experience mild changes in mood, such as feeling more energetic, optimistic, or sensitive.</p>\n    <p>It\'s important to remember that the effects of hormones on mood can vary from person to person, and some individuals may be more sensitive or responsive to hormonal changes than others. Factors such as overall mental health, stress levels, and individual differences can also influence mood during the follicular phase.</p>\n    <p>If you are experiencing mood swings or significant changes in mood that affect your daily life and well-being during the follicular phase or at any other point in your menstrual cycle, it\'s a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide personalized advice and support to help manage your symptoms.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Mood swings during your ovulation</span></h1>\n    <p>Mood swings during ovulation are relatively less common compared to the premenstrual phase or menstruation itself. However, some individuals may still experience mild mood changes during this time due to hormonal fluctuations.</p>\n    <p>During ovulation, there is a surge in estrogen levels followed by a rise in luteinizing hormone (LH), which triggers the release of the egg from the ovary. While these hormonal changes primarily focus on preparing the body for potential pregnancy, they can also influence mood and emotions to some extent.</p>\n    <p>Some individuals may experience subtle mood swings during ovulation, which can range from feeling more energized, confident, or cheerful to being slightly more sensitive or irritable. However, these mood swings are typically milder compared to the more noticeable changes that occur during the premenstrual phase.</p>\n    <p>If you find that your mood swings during ovulation are severe, persistent, or significantly impact your daily life, it\'s a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide personalized advice and support, evaluate any underlying factors, and discuss management strategies if necessary.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Mood swings during your luteal phase</span></h1>\n    <p>Mood swings during the first days of the luteal phase are considered more common and normal. The luteal phase is the second half of the menstrual cycle, occurring after ovulation and leading up to menstruation. During this phase, the levels of estrogen and progesterone rise and then decline if pregnancy does not occur.</p>\n    <p>The hormonal changes that occur during the luteal phase can affect neurotransmitters in the brain, potentially leading to mood swings and changes in emotions. Many women may experience mild mood changes, such as feeling more irritable, moody, anxious, or having heightened sensitivity during this time.</p>\n    <p>These mood swings are often associated with premenstrual syndrome (PMS), which can occur during the luteal phase. It\'s important to note that the severity and duration of mood swings can vary from person to person. Some individuals may experience more pronounced mood swings, while others may have milder or no noticeable changes in mood.</p>\n    <p>If your mood swings during the first days of the luteal phase are severe, significantly impact your daily life, or cause distress, it\'s a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide personalized advice, evaluate any underlying factors, and discuss management strategies if necessary.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Mood swings during your PMS</span></h1>\n    <p>Mood swings during the last part of the luteal phase, often referred to as late luteal phase or premenstrual phase, are quite common and considered normal. During this time, hormone levels, particularly estrogen and progesterone, are on the decline in preparation for menstruation.</p>\n    <p>The hormonal fluctuations and changes in neurotransmitters that occur during the late luteal phase can impact mood and emotions. Many women experience mood swings and changes in emotions during this period. These mood swings can include feelings of irritability, sadness, anxiety, or being easily overwhelmed.</p>\n    <p>These mood swings are often associated with premenstrual syndrome (PMS) or its more severe form, premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD). It\'s important to note that the severity and duration of mood swings can vary from person to person. Some individuals may experience mild mood swings, while others may have more pronounced changes in mood.</p>\n    <p>If your mood swings during the late luteal phase are severe, significantly impact your daily life, or cause distress, it\'s a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide personalized advice, evaluate any underlying factors, and discuss management strategies if necessary.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Anxiety or depression increase during your menstruation</span></h1>\n    <p> It is relatively common for some individuals to experience increased depression and/or anxiety symptoms during their menstruation. This is often referred to as \"menstrual-related mood disorders\" and can include conditions such as premenstrual syndrome (PMS) or premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD).</p>\n    <p>The hormonal fluctuations that occur during the menstrual cycle can affect neurotransmitters in the brain, potentially impacting mood and emotions. For some individuals, this hormonal shift can lead to an exacerbation of depressive or anxious symptoms. It\'s important to note that these symptoms typically arise in the premenstrual or menstrual phase and may improve as the cycle progresses.</p>\n    <p>If you notice a significant increase in depressive or anxious symptoms that occur consistently during your menstruation and interfere with your daily life and well-being, it is recommended to consult with a healthcare professional. They can evaluate your symptoms, provide a proper diagnosis, and discuss appropriate treatment options.</p>\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Anxiety or depression increase during your follicular</span></h1>\n    <p> While increased depression and/or anxiety during the follicular phase of the menstrual cycle is less common compared to the premenstrual phase, it is possible for some individuals to experience such symptoms during this time. The follicular phase occurs at the beginning of the menstrual cycle, leading up to ovulation.</p>\n    <p>During the follicular phase, estrogen levels gradually rise, which can have an impact on mood and emotions. While most individuals may not experience significant changes in depression or anxiety during this phase, some may notice subtle shifts in mood. This can include feeling more energized, optimistic, or experiencing increased mental clarity.</p>\n    <p>It\'s important to note that the effects of hormones on mood can vary from person to person, and some individuals may be more sensitive or responsive to hormonal changes than others. Factors such as overall mental health, stress levels, and individual differences can also influence mood during the follicular phase.</p>\n    <p>If you find that you experience increased depression or anxiety symptoms during the follicular phase that significantly impact your daily life and well-being, it\'s a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide personalized advice, evaluate any underlying factors, and discuss management strategies if necessary.</p>\n\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Anxiety or depression increase during your ovulation</span></h1>\n    <p> Increased depression and/or anxiety during ovulation is less common compared to the premenstrual phase or menstruation itself. Ovulation is the process when the egg is released from the ovary, and hormonal changes occur as part of the menstrual cycle.</p>\n    <p>During ovulation, there is a surge in estrogen levels followed by a rise in luteinizing hormone (LH). These hormonal changes primarily focus on preparing the body for potential pregnancy and are generally associated with increased energy, a heightened sense of well-being, and improved mood for most individuals.</p>\n    <p>While it is less typical to experience increased depression or anxiety during ovulation, it\'s important to note that everyone\'s experience can be different. Factors such as individual sensitivity to hormonal changes, underlying mental health conditions, and other life stressors can influence mood during this time.</p>\n    <p>If you consistently experience increased depression or anxiety symptoms during ovulation that significantly impact your daily life and well-being, it\'s recommended to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide a thorough evaluation, discuss any underlying factors, and determine the best course of action for managing your symptoms.</p>\n\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Anxiety or depression increase during your luteal phase</span></h1>\n    <p> It is relatively common for some individuals to experience increased depression and/or anxiety symptoms during the beginning of the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle. The luteal phase occurs after ovulation and is characterized by increased levels of progesterone and, to a lesser extent, estrogen.</p>\n    <p>During the early days of the luteal phase, hormone levels are elevated, and then they gradually decline if pregnancy does not occur. These hormonal fluctuations can affect neurotransmitters in the brain, potentially leading to changes in mood and emotions.</p>\n    <p>Some individuals may experience increased feelings of depression, anxiety, irritability, or other mood-related symptoms during this time. These symptoms are often associated with premenstrual syndrome (PMS) or premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD). It\'s important to note that the severity and duration of symptoms can vary from person to person.</p>\n    <p>If you find that you consistently experience increased depression or anxiety symptoms during the beginning of the luteal phase that significantly impact your daily life and well-being, it\'s a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide a proper evaluation, discuss potential underlying factors, and recommend appropriate management strategies.</p>\n\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n\n',
    '<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n\n<head>\n    <title>Menstrual Period Changes</title>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n    <h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Anxiety or depression increase during your PMS</span></h1>\n    <p> It is relatively common for some individuals to experience increased depression and/or anxiety symptoms during the ending of the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle. The late luteal phase, also known as the premenstrual phase, occurs in the days leading up to menstruation.</p>\n    <p>During this time, hormone levels, particularly progesterone, start to decline as the body prepares for menstruation. These hormonal changes, along with other factors, can contribute to mood fluctuations and increased emotional sensitivity.</p>\n    <p>Many individuals may experience mood changes, including increased feelings of depression, anxiety, irritability, or other premenstrual symptoms during the ending of the luteal phase. These symptoms are often associated with premenstrual syndrome (PMS) or its more severe form, premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD). It\'s important to note that the severity and duration of symptoms can vary from person to person.</p>\n    <p>If you consistently experience increased depression or anxiety symptoms during the ending of the luteal phase that significantly impact your daily life and well-being, it\'s recommended to consult with a healthcare professional. They can provide a proper evaluation, discuss potential underlying factors, and recommend appropriate management strategies.</p>\n\n    <p><br></p>\n</body>\n</html>\n'
